feels strange to be so sincere on main but I was just kind of thinking about it and started typing it. felt like I needed to share
trans people deserve joy.
that's why medically transitioning helped me feel more okay with being me. it taught me to trust myself and that I deserve to experience joy.

obviously (lol) I still have anxiety, but getting top surgery kind of surprisingly ended up serving a significant exposure therapy role for me. it taught me that it's safe to trust myself on a very fundamental level that I didn't even realize was possible before.

I worried that I wouldn't be able to handle the surgery or recovery processes, worried I would regret my choice, worried about what others would think, worried about an accident in the OR. you name it, I worried about it, in a cycle with all the other worries, constantly.

I had SO much anxiety leading up to getting top surgery, and it was honestly controlling my life. I was obsessed with trying to plan for every possible outcome scenario after surgery, and i couldn't escape it. I was sure something would go wrong.
I've had this feeling a bit less since allowing myself the space to medically transition in the ways that called to me. when dysphoria does arise, it's easier to recognize and to expreience

when my dysphoria manifests itself, it typically feels like I'm not okay at all, that something big, looming, overwhelming, and catastrophic is wrong. this feels very similar to how anxiety does for me, but it's gender-based and has its own nuances and patterns within dysphoria
my wish for every trans person is that in whatever ways right for them, that they can find more peace within themself. medical transition has brought a lot of peace to me.

for me, the thing about "medically transitioning" is that getting top surgery made me being who I am feel more okay. going on hormones made me being who I am feel more okay. made it feel much more okay on a deep inner level
